  "prompt": "Are there international laws against money laundering?",
  "response": "Yes, there are international laws and frameworks designed to combat money laundering. The primary international organization leading the charge against money laundering is the **Financial Action Task Force (FATF)**. Established in 1989, the FATF sets global standards and promotes effective implementation of legal, regulatory, and operational measures to combat money laundering, terrorist financing, and other related threats to the integrity of the international financial system.\n\n### Key International Frameworks and Laws:\n1. **FATF Recommendations**: The FATF has developed a set of 40 Recommendations, which are internationally recognized as the global standard for anti-money laundering (AML) and counter-terrorist financing (CTF) measures. These recommendations provide a comprehensive framework for countries to develop their AML/CFT regimes.\n\n2. **United Nations Conventions**:\n   - **United Nations Convention against Illicit Traffic in Narcotic Drugs and Psychotropic Substances (1988)**: Known as the Vienna Convention, it was the first international treaty to address money laundering, specifically in the context of drug trafficking.\n   - **United Nations Convention against Transnational Organized Crime (2000)**: Also known as the Palermo Convention, it includes provisions to combat money laundering related to organized crime.\n   - **United Nations Convention against Corruption (2003)**: The Merida Convention addresses money laundering as part of broader efforts to combat corruption.\n\n3. **European Union Directives**:\n   - The EU has issued several **Anti-Money Laundering Directives (AMLDs)**, which require Member States to implement AML/CFT measures. The latest, the **6th Anti-Money Laundering Directive (6AMLD)**, strengthens criminal sanctions and expands the scope of predicate offenses.\n\n4. **Basel Committee on Banking Supervision**: While not legally binding, the Basel Committee provides guidelines and principles for banks to establish effective AML procedures, such as the **Basel AML Index**.\n\n5. **International Monetary Fund (IMF) and World Bank**: These organizations assist countries in implementing AML/CFT measures and assess compliance with FATF standards as part of their financial sector oversight.\n\n### Enforcement and Compliance:\nCountries are expected to implement these international standards into their domestic laws. The FATF conducts mutual evaluations to assess countries' compliance with its recommendations and identifies jurisdictions with strategic deficiencies (e.g., the FATF \"grey list\" and \"black list\").\n\n### Key Principles of AML Laws:\n- **Criminalization of Money Laundering**: Making money laundering a criminal offense.\n- **Customer Due Diligence (CDD)**: Financial institutions must identify and verify customers and monitor transactions.\n- **Reporting Suspicious Activities**: Mandatory reporting of suspicious transactions to financial intelligence units (FIUs).\n- **International Cooperation**: Encouraging cross-border cooperation and information sharing.\n\nThese international efforts aim to create a unified global response to the challenges posed by money laundering and related financial crimes.",
  "temperature": 1.0,
